With the government’s moves to ramp up medical tourism, improving reproductive health facilities and services should be a priority, she added.

“We are often told how easy it is for Cuban doctors to leave, to get postgraduate training in Europe or elsewhere. But what about African scholars enrolled in Cuban medical schools? Are they allowed to stay and work there? On the contrary, Cubans are fiercely protected,” she noted.

Despite having a government that provides free medical treatment to all residents, Cuba’s reproductive health status bears only a distant resemblance to the medical marvel which made the island a byword for medical excellence internationally, due in part to the government’s uncharacteristic approach. Indeed, the sex education provided – or lack thereof, as the case may be – to local youth is fundamental to the bubbling reproductive health crisis the country’s confronted with today.

However, even more alarming still is repeated attempts to simplify the otherwise complex matter of reproductive health and education by naming it “pro-abortion” as if the primary objective of it is to champion child killing. Equally worrying remains efforts by the Cuban government to curtail youth access to birth control and abortion.
